<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" box="[151,245,506,531]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">Females</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<keyStep pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" box="[151,1435,542,563]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,542,563]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
1. Entirely black (
<figureCitation box="[373,428,542,563]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1962,1984]" captionTargetBox="[168,1420,290,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,274,1937]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus. A. Anoplius (Dicranoplius) albidus holotype female; B. A. (D.) areatus female; C. A. (D.) brevitarsus female; D. A. (D.) brevitarsus male; E. A. (D.) cujanus female; and F. A. (D.) cujanus male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/848431/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
e); first tarsal segment of front leg with four comb-spines................ 
<taxonomicName authority="(Holmberg)" authorityName="Holmberg" box="[1171,1435,542,563]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Pompilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cujanus" subGenus="Dicranoplius">
<emphasis box="[1171,1185,542,563]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">A</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[1205,1222,542,563]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">D</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1242,1317,542,563]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">cujanus</emphasis>
(Holmberg)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
-. Metasoma orange or reddish, at least in large part (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[775,840,571,592]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1962,1984]" captionTargetBox="[168,1420,290,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,274,1937]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus. A. Anoplius (Dicranoplius) albidus holotype female; B. A. (D.) areatus female; C. A. (D.) brevitarsus female; D. A. (D.) brevitarsus male; E. A. (D.) cujanus female; and F. A. (D.) cujanus male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/848431/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
a,c); first tarsal segment of front leg with three comb spines (except sometimes a small forth spine in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Taschenberg" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[618,761,601,622]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Anoplius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="areatus" subGenus="Dicranoplius">
<emphasis box="[618,633,601,622]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">A</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[653,670,601,622]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">D</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[690,761,601,622]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">areatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[761,768,601,622]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">)</emphasis>
......................................................2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
2. Pubescence of head and mesosoma wholly dark (
<figureCitation box="[699,766,630,651]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1835,1857]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,191,1800]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,191,1806]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Habitus. A. Anoplius (Dicranoplius) diphonichus, male; B. A. (D.) nigritus holotype male; C. A. (D.) nigritus female; D. A. (D.) pompero allotype female; E. A. (D.) pompero paratype male; and F. A. (D.) satanus female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/848433/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
c,d,f &amp; 3b), if front and clypeus and along posterior margin of pronotum silvery, remainder of mesosoma with black setae.........................................................3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
-. Pubescence of head, mesosoma and metasoma silvery with black setae maculations, at least on front, clypeus, and along posterior margin of pronotum and mesoscutum (
<figureCitation box="[637,701,718,739]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1962,1984]" captionTargetBox="[168,1420,290,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,274,1937]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus. A. Anoplius (Dicranoplius) albidus holotype female; B. A. (D.) areatus female; C. A. (D.) brevitarsus female; D. A. (D.) brevitarsus male; E. A. (D.) cujanus female; and F. A. (D.) cujanus male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/848431/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
a,b,c).......................................................8
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
3. Apical tergum of metasoma with stout bristles; slope of propodeum low with the declivity ill-defined; metasoma sometimes, but not always, black beyond basal 2.5 segments........................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="(Evans)" authorityName="Evans" box="[1208,1435,777,798]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Dicranoplius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigritus" subGenus="Dicranoplius">
<emphasis box="[1208,1223,777,798]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">A</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[1243,1260,777,798]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">D</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1281,1356,777,798]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">nigritus</emphasis>
(Evans)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead pageId="12" pageNumber="549">-. Apical tergum of metasoma with only thin setae; propodeum more convex and with a strong declivity; metasoma always wholly orange or reddish................................................................................3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
4. Comb spines very short, shorter than width of tarsus; pronotum, in profile, rather flat and with a nearly perpendicular anterior face; propodeum very short and strongly convex...................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="(Taschenberg)" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Taschenberg" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[1150,1435,894,915]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Anoplius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="areatus" subGenus="Dicranoplius">
<emphasis box="[1150,1165,894,915]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">A</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[1185,1202,894,915]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">D</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1222,1293,894,915]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">areatus</emphasis>
(Taschenberg)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" box="[151,1435,924,945]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,924,945]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">-. Comb spines longer than width of tarsus; pronotum sloping rather smoothly in profile; propodeum longer and less convex ... 5</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
5. Slope of propodeum rather low, the declivity ill-defined; length of fore wing about 
<quantity box="[1022,1080,953,974]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="549" unit="mm" value="8.0">8 mm</quantity>
; clypeus about 3× as wide as high................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="(Evans)" authorityName="Evans" box="[1199,1435,982,1003]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Dicranoplius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pampero" subGenus="Dicranoplius">
<emphasis box="[1199,1213,982,1003]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">A</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[1234,1251,982,1003]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">D</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1271,1355,982,1003]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">pampero</emphasis>
(Evans)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
-. Slope of propodeum higher and more convex, with a distinct flattened posterior declivity; fore wing 
<quantity box="[1207,1302,1012,1033]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="12" pageNumber="549" unit="mm" value="11.0" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="9.0">9–13 mm</quantity>
; clypeus 2.5– 2.8× as wide as high...................................................................................6
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
6. Propodeum with a number of erect setae AND antennal flagellum orange or reddish, often dusky on upper surface (
<figureCitation box="[1332,1389,1070,1091]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1835,1857]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,191,1800]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,191,1806]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Habitus. A. Anoplius (Dicranoplius) diphonichus, male; B. A. (D.) nigritus holotype male; C. A. (D.) nigritus female; D. A. (D.) pompero allotype female; E. A. (D.) pompero paratype male; and F. A. (D.) satanus female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/848433/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
f)................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Holmberg)" authorityName="Holmberg" box="[1172,1435,1100,1121]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Pompilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="satanus" subGenus="Dicranoplius">
<emphasis box="[1172,1187,1100,1121]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">A</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[1206,1223,1100,1121]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">D</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1244,1317,1100,1121]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">satanus</emphasis>
(Holmberg)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" box="[151,1436,1129,1150]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1129,1150]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">-. Propodeum not at all setose OR antennal flagellum black......................................................7</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
7. Ocelli form a right triangle; antennal flagellum orange or reddish, often dusky on upper.................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Pitts and Sadler" authorityName="Sadler" authorityYear="2017" box="[1058,1350,1188,1209]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Anoplius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="evansi" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Dicranoplius">
<emphasis box="[1058,1073,1188,1209]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">A</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[1093,1110,1188,1209]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">D</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1130,1191,1188,1209]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">evansi</emphasis>
Pitts and Sadler
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1359,1436,1187,1209]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1359,1436,1187,1209]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" box="[151,1436,1217,1238]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1217,1238]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
-. Ocelli form an oblique triangle; antennal flagellum black............................... 
<taxonomicName authority="(Spinola)" authorityName="Spinola" box="[1151,1436,1217,1238]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Anoplius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diphonichus" subGenus="Dicranoplius">
<emphasis box="[1151,1166,1217,1238]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">A</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[1186,1203,1217,1238]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">D</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1223,1340,1217,1238]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">diphonichus</emphasis>
(Spinola)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" box="[151,1436,1246,1267]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1246,1267]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
8. Vertex strongly arched above eye tops................................................ 
<taxonomicName authority="(Banks)" authorityName="Banks" box="[1175,1436,1246,1267]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Austrochares" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevitarsus" subGenus="Dicranoplius">
<emphasis box="[1175,1189,1246,1267]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">A</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[1210,1227,1246,1267]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">D</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1247,1354,1246,1267]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">brevitarsus</emphasis>
(Banks)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" box="[151,1436,1276,1297]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1276,1297]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">-. Vertex passing nearly straight across at or near eye tops.......................................................9</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
9. Head subcircular, widest near middle; vertex with a broad dark band; propodeum with dark pubescence at least anteriorly; antennal segments short, dorsal interocular distance approximately 1.7× longer than first flagellomere length........................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="(Taschenberg)" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Taschenberg" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[1150,1435,1364,1385]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Anoplius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="areatus" subGenus="Dicranoplius">
<emphasis box="[1150,1165,1364,1385]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">A</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[1185,1202,1364,1385]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">D</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1222,1293,1364,1385]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">areatus</emphasis>
(Taschenberg)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,506,1473]" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
<keyLead pageId="12" pageNumber="549">
-. Head widest well above middle; vertex wholly silvery-pubescent except at ocellar triangle; propodeum wholly silvery; antennal segments longer, dorsal interocular distance approximately 1.2× longer than first flagellomere length................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="(Evans)" authorityName="Evans" box="[1212,1435,1452,1473]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Anoplius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albidus" subGenus="Dicranoplius">
<emphasis box="[1212,1227,1452,1473]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">A</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[1247,1264,1452,1473]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">D</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1284,1355,1452,1473]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="549">albidus</emphasis>
(Evans)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
